In the image below i have a snippet. In the body of the loop the syntax colors seem messed up.
The way to fix it is adding a space before the < and then the colors are normal.

I have this problem in version 0.10.10 and had it in the previous version.

![syntaxcolors](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2932769/13675051/24d87098-e6e0-11e5-9735-33b45a379967.png)

Snippet:

```
for(var i=0;i<10;++i){
  // Weird colors
  for(var i=0;i<10;++i){
    // Weird colors
  }
}
// Normal color
for(var i=0;i <10;++i){
  for(var i=0;i <10;++i){
  }
}
```

This is an odd set of circumstances, but it causes v10.10 to crash (on Windows), and it didn't in 10.8, so I'll report it anyway. I was experiencing a lot of crashes while developing autocomplete in an extension, and found that it boiled down to this:

If an extension provides a _LanguageConfiguration_ with a _wordPattern_ that can match an empty string (eg `/\w*/`), and it then registers a _CompletionItemProvider_ that provides no completion items (an empty array): the intellisense will show "Loading..." for about 10 seconds, then vscode will crash.

Here's example code ([full sample attached](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/files/167431/abc-completionitems.zip)). This extension creates a new language "abc" with extension ".abc".

``` ts
import * as vscode from 'vscode';
import { TextDocument, Position, CancellationToken, CompletionItem, languages } from 'vscode';

const languageConfiguration: vscode.LanguageConfiguration = {
    wordPattern: /\w*/
}

export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) 
{
    context.subscriptions.push(
        languages.setLanguageConfiguration('abc', languageConfiguration));

    context.subscriptions.push(
        languages.registerCompletionItemProvider('abc', new CompletionItemProvider()));
}

class CompletionItemProvider implements vscode.CompletionItemProvider {
    provideCompletionItems(
        document: TextDocument, position: Position, token: CancellationToken)
        : CompletionItem[]
    {
        return [];
    }
}
```

Both conditions must be true: if the completion provider provides at least one result then it's shown without a problem. If the wordPattern is a valid one then the intellisense shows "No suggestions." for an empty array without problem.

I think it can also cause crashes with a hover provider too but I haven't pinned that one down.
